</div><div class="episode" id="episode_414">
  <div class="screenshot"><a href="/episodes/59-optimistic-locking-revised"><img alt="Optimistic Locking (revised)" height="125" src="/static/episodes/stills/059-optimistic-locking-revised.png" width="200" /></a></div>
  <div class="main">
    <div class="info">
      <span class="number">Episode #59</span> &ndash;
      <span class="published_at">Aug 04, 2012</span> &ndash;
      <span class="comments"><a href="/episodes/59-optimistic-locking-revised?view=comments">6 comments</a></span>
    </div>
    <h2>
      <a href="/episodes/59-optimistic-locking-revised">Optimistic Locking (revised)</a>
      
    </h2>
    <div class="description">
      There is a chance one user will unintentionally override  someone else&#x27;s changes if they update a record near the same time. One solution is to use optimistic locking. The updated_at column can also be used for this as shown.
      <span class="stats">(8 minutes)</span>
    </div>
    <div class="watch">
        <a href="/pro" class="pretty_button">Subscribe to Watch Episode</a>
    </div>
  </div>
